    # [Scene: Community Hall | Night — Rain]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, insistent piano — steady, purposeful]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain on tin roof; distant gulls like soft punctuation]
    "You remember the way your hand curled around the edge of the table — the small, decisive motion that unlatched the rest of the evening. You left with a paper-thin certainty: demand a regulated review. It"
    "felt like a boundary you had to set for the future you wanted, even if it cost the present."
    "The hall smells of wet wool and coffee gone cold. People file out in pairs and quiet knots, voices low, frayed. Tamsin's tablet glows in the dark like a calm, unreadable tide. Corinne has already left;"
    "there is a rumor of her in the air, a thin, efficient cold that travels faster than bodies."
    "Abuela Rosa meets you by the exit. The shawl at her shoulders is damp at the edges; she presses a palm to your forearm — not demanding, only weighing you with sight that has weathered far worse seasons than this one."
    show abuela_rosa at left:
        zoom 0.7

    abuela_rosa "You chose the long road, niña. It is honest work, but it asks patience and teeth. Are you ready to carry that slow kind of weight?"
    "You taste salt and metal on your tongue as you answer. Your words come measured — not a plea, not a retreat."
    show amaya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_reyes "I am. For now, it's the clearest thing: regulatory review buys time to build protections the town actually wants."
    "Abuela Rosa's eyes go distant and then bright, like someone who finds the smallest useful seed in a field of stones."

    abuela_rosa "Then carry it as you would a lamp. Let it show others the way, but know it will not warm every hand."
    "You swallow and nod. Night pulls the meeting apart. Outside, the storm doesn't feel angry — just inevitable."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain softens; footfalls on wet wood]
    hide abuela_rosa
    hide amaya_reyes

    scene bg ch15_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # [Scene: Construction Site — Early Morning]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Steady strings, mid-tempo — momentum without panic]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant thud of pile drivers; measured radio chatter]
    "They moved faster than the speed of outrage. You watch the machines from the edge of the site, where a temporary fence keeps the public out and the town's view in. Voss's banners flap in precise"
    "blues: PROTECTION • PROGRESS • JOBS. Corinne stands near the plans, gloved and cool, an island of purpose amid diesel and dust."
    "Tamsin arrives, breath fogging in the morning air. She is apologetic in a way that looks like fatigue folded into civic duty."
    show tamsin_cho at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tamsin_cho "They pushed the council. Emergency permissions—economic pressure, contractors standing by. I'm sorry, Amaya. I tried to stall, but—"
    "You listen. The sentence finishes itself in your chest: they moved. You name the mechanics — a vote swung by promises, a deadline, a fund dangling over worn hands — and still you feel the curious"
    "warmth of clarity. You demanded review; the system reacted. The town will now live inside the consequences of that reaction."
    "Corinne hears Tamsin and approaches. Her face is softer this morning, not unkind but fixtured into strategy."
    show corinne_voss at right:
        zoom 0.7

    corinne_voss "We moved because delay risks collapse. People need work. If we redline protections and keep construction paused, the bay will make the choice for us."
    "You step forward. You do not shout. There is no theatrics; only the even cadence of someone using facts like a rope."
    show amaya_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_reyes "The risk of displacement is a human cost. It's not abstract. The review can protect infrastructure without making neighborhood displacement the price. We could co-design buffer systems, fund temporary housing that keeps people in town—"
    "Corinne interrupts with a quiet efficiency that is almost apologetic."

    corinne_voss "We have to make hard calls. You understand that. I'm not heartless — I'm practical. We cannot afford indefinite pauses."
    "The exchange has the shape of compromise and the texture of irreconcilable calendars. Machines rumble closer. A family with a single battered van waits by the site entrance; a volunteer from TideLab unloads boxes with calm"
    "hands. You notice small scenes as if cataloguing tiles of a larger mosaic: neighbors carrying one another's fragile heirlooms; contractors offering a worker's small courtesy to a displaced elder; Abuela Rosa watching from a safe distance,"
    "hands clasped as if in prayer or calculation."

    menu:
        "Step in and offer mediation to delay a single demolition":
            "You approach the site foreman, voice steady. He listens; you broker a six-hour pause to move possessions from a house at the edge of the zone. The family breathes out, and you feel the temporary warmth of a small rescue."
        "Document everything and send the footage to the press":
            "You hand Jules your recorder; he shoots steady frames as homes are cordoned. The footage spreads fast, a thread of public scrutiny that hums in the town's veins later that day. You feel less immediately useful but see the seed of leverage."

    # --- merge ---
    "Both choices leave you with the same new fact: the town is being redrawn by contracts and concrete."
    "The foreman is pragmatic; the pause is small but real. The camera runs; the images will haunt headlines. Both choices leave you with the same new fact: the town is being redrawn by contracts and concrete."
    # [Scene: Boardwalk — Midday]
    hide tamsin_cho
    hide corinne_voss
    hide amaya_reyes

    scene bg ch15_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single cello line, warm, carrying forward]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Conversation like distant surf; the muffled clank of crates; a woman's laugh under strain]
    "The boardwalk is now a junction of claims. Some families accept relocation assistance — a clean truck, a counselor, a promise of new footing. Others stick to foundations and family names painted on porch posts, choosing legal limbo over being uprooted."
    "Mateo stands before one of the houses, jaw tight, hands keeping pace with his words."
    show mateo_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_reyes "They say they'll relocate us to the new development. They say it'll be 'modern' and 'safe'. But it's not our harbor. It's not the smell of fishbones and kelp in the morning, Maja."
    "You feel the name like a splinter. Mateo looks to you for the thing you have been trying to be: a steward who can translate policy into shelter, who can hold the town's ledger and its heart at the same time."
    show amaya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_reyes "We will keep fighting for better terms. We will appeal. We will use every legal lever to make sure people can come back, or that relocation keeps community ties intact."
    "Mateo folds and unfolds his hands. You both know the truth — promises are paper and promises are leverage. Still, his voice holds a small bright stubbornness that steadies you."
    "The boardwalk is also where you find Luka that afternoon, leaning on a railing as if listening to the tide. The sun trims his silhouette; he looks older, as if the last months etched lines into his patience."
    show luka_maren at center:
        zoom 0.7

    luka_maren "Amaya."
    "Your name in his mouth stops the crowd noise into a private room. He does not hide the guilt in his face; it sits there like a transparent thing. He reaches into his smock and pulls out a contract envelope, folded and official."

    luka_maren "I took the consultancy. It wasn't because I like their clauses. It was because—' (he gestures at the machines) '—there's a way to save tech from the inside. I can push for open designs, make sure sensors and modular units are accessible, not locked down. I kept trying to do the small, but sometimes the small needs leverage from the big."
    "You feel the sentence land like a stone dropped into your own chest pool. Disappointment swells, but not like a rupture: more like a tide change that rearranges the shoreline."

    amaya_reyes "We spent years trying to build trust so we wouldn't have to be inside deals like that. If you go in, don't let them steal the designs. If you go in—come back to tell us what they change."
    "Luka Maren runs a hand through his hair, the motion tired and earnest."

    luka_maren "I won't let them patent the parts that matter. I can't fix everything from outside anymore. I wish—' (he falters) '—I wish I could promise I'll be here."
    "The conversation stretches new and old lines. He wants to be useful on a broader scale; you want him present where the town breathes. Both are true. You say nothing sharp. What you offer is steadier, a bridge without promises."

    amaya_reyes "Do it the way you can live with. And keep the TideLab channels open. If you see a way to make their tech open, do it. But promise me you'll tell me when they make a move we can't let stand."

    luka_maren "I promise I'll tell you. I'm sorry."
    "His apology knocks at the thin lacquer of your composure. You close your eyes and let the sea sound fill that small empty place. There is sorrow here, but also a kind of acceptance: people choose different strategies for the same hope."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A gentle rise — strings warming into a hopeful chord]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A gull calls; a distant sawing of wood]
    # [Scene: TideLab | Late Afternoon]
    hide mateo_reyes
    hide amaya_reyes
    hide luka_maren

    scene bg ch15_3be532_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet, steady harmonies — contemplative but forward-moving]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft clink of tools, low conversation, the hum of a battery bank]
    "Inside, volunteers sort data, prepare petitions, and call legal friends. Jules edits footage from the morning. The mood is sober but not broken. People compare lists: names of those who accepted relocation; names of those who refused. You feel like a conductor of small, fragile instruments."
    "Abuela Rosa sits at the workbench, knitting something that looks suspiciously like a repaired net. She looks up when you enter."
    show abuela_rosa at left:
        zoom 0.7

    abuela_rosa "You will go, niña? You think leaving will be abandoning?"
    "You consider the question like one checks a map. Leaving is not fleeing; it's strategic — a fellowship to build leverage and connections beyond the bay. You picture the ledger again, expanded: a regional network, legal"
    "partners, sympathetic journalists, other towns learning from the fight. Distance could be a new kind of reach."
    show amaya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_reyes "I am not leaving forever. I'm taking a fellowship. I will learn, network, and bring back tools we can't make here alone. This is a different kind of defense."
    "Abuela Rosa taps her needle against the table as if stamping a small approval."

    abuela_rosa "Then go with a clear heart. Fight for this place with the muscle of the broader world behind you. But always answer the call to come home."
    "You smile, a small, firm thing. There is guilt, yes, for not standing in every doorway when the bulldozers move. There is pain for the relationships rearranged — for Luka's distance, for neighbors who will spend"
    "winters in apartments far from the salt. But underneath the ache is a steady thread of purpose: you will transform the grief into strategy."

    menu:
        "Leave your field notebook on the TideLab table for Mateo with notes for local actions":
            "You scribble a plan in the margins — contacts, a timeline, steps to contest permits — and leave the notebook where he will find it. It is a way to be present. The notebook feels warm with your intention."
        "Take the notebook with you as a symbol of continuity":
            "You slide the leather-bound book into your bag, the tide maps tucked inside. It feels like carrying home with you. You'll use it to teach other towns what you learned here."

    # --- merge ---
    "Both choices keep a thread of continuity between you and the town — either an anchor left behind or a symbol carried forward."
    "The volunteers laugh softly at an inside joke about kelp sensors. The laughter is small and stubborn and true. You help pack a crate of spare sensors to send to a legal ally. These are not"
    "grand victories. They are the incremental tools that may one day turn local losses into shared knowledge."
    # [Scene: Boardwalk — Dawn, Days Later]
    hide abuela_rosa
    hide amaya_reyes

    scene bg ch15_3be532_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm major key strings — contemplative triumph in a small register]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low machinery, a softer wind, a child's call in the distance]
    "Departure is always both a closing and an opening. You zip your jacket against the harbor chill and fasten the braided bracelet of wildflower seeds around your wrist the way Abuela taught you — three knots for three things: memory, promise, return."
    "Mateo meets you by the ferry. He carries a small box of items he couldn't fit in the relocation van: a battered radio, a jar of preserved lemons, a photograph of your father with a grin"
    "like a weather vane. He hands you a small stone from the shore — smooth, warmed by hands — a talisman."
    show mateo_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_reyes "Don't forget why you left, hermana. Bring us learning. Bring us power."
    "You hold the stone like a prayer."
    show amaya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_reyes "I will come back with tools and rules that help keep people here. I will not let this be just a memory."
    "He studies you with that stubborn love that is supply and compass both."

    mateo_reyes "Then go. Make the world stand for us."
    "The ferry slides away from the concrete quay with a muted mechanical sigh. As the town recedes, the seawall's first lines glitter like a new, harsh horizon. It is a protection — and also a scar. You feel both truths at once, plainly and without collapse."

    "Inside your notebook, you write a single line in the margin above a map" "For Marisol Bay — fight hard, return harder."
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single, sustaining violin note that doesn't mourn so much as settle into resolve]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Water against hull; gulls wheel and then settle]
    "You leave Marisol Bay with the ache of a place you love and the bright, stubborn belief that leaving can be a way to build return. It will not fix the houses already moved or the"
    "dinners changed into cardboard boxes. It will not mend every friendship that stretched thin. But distance gives leverage, networks, and a platform. You will turn local failure into a wider case study, a caution and a"
    "blueprint."
    "You are haunted — yes — but your haunting is not paralyzing. It is a tool. You fold it into research proposals, op-eds, coalition calls. You carry the town's ledger like a lit map, and the fellowship will teach you how to read other ledgers better."
    "Outside, the bay opens, and a new, uncertain horizon accepts you. You will fight from there, with the town in your chest and the wider world in your plans."
    hide mateo_reyes
    hide amaya_reyes

    scene bg ch15_3be532_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Swells gently then settles — hopeful, not oblivious]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant construction continues; life goes on]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_8 at full_bg
    "THE END"
